******
[1] Washington DC
Date: Mon 10 Nov 2014
Source: The Washington Post [edited]
http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/crime/georgetown-university-student-expected-to-be-sentenced-for-possessing-ricin/2014/11/10/318c4466-68d5-11e4-9fb4-a622dae742a2_story.html


A Georgetown University student who was arrested for manufacturing the deadly chemical ricin in his dormitory room in March [2014], was sentenced [Mon 10 Nov 2014] in a US district court to a year and a day in prison.

In issuing her sentence, Judge Ketanji B Jackson said the student perpetrator's intentions for manufacturing the chemical were "ambiguous at best" but that the student put numerous people, including his classmates and dormitory roommate, at great risk. Jackson also ordered [the 20 year old student] to undergo a mental health evaluation, serve 2 years of supervised probation, and perform 400 hours of community service. The convicted student has been in an isolation cell in DC jail since his arrest. Attorneys say the student could be moved to a halfway house in January [2015] because of the 7.5 months of jail time he has served already, which is being credited to his sentence.

The convicted student pleaded guilty in September [2014] to unregistered possession of a biological agent or toxin. Before he was sentenced, the student, dressed in an orange Department of Corrections jumpsuit, apologized as 70 friends and family members, including his parents, looked on. "I never intended to put anyone in any risk of danger. My actions were reckless and unacceptable," he said. The Bethesda native apologized to his family, friends, and the university. "I am sorry I broke the trust you placed in me," he said.

The student's attorneys said he had no plans to harm anyone other than himself when he met with a classmate and student resident adviser on 17 Mar 2014 and, according to court charging documents, pulled out a double-wrapped plastic bag and tossed it on the floor, telling his friend that the bag contained ricin, which he had manufactured in his dorm room while on school break. The adviser alerted authorities.

The student's attorney, Danny Onorato, told the judge his client had planned to use the deadly poison to commit suicide as a result of years of mental and emotional problems that were diagnosed when the student was 10. "He was depressed and suicidal," Onorato said. He added that the student, a science major who had planned to become a medical doctor, did not want to kill himself in a way that would cause emotional distress to his parents and family, such as by hanging. The student, Onorato said, instead researched how to make ricin.

But prosecutors Maia L Miller and Frederick W Yette characterized the student as having had a calculated plan and asked the judge for a 2-year sentence. Miller said the student searched for a "recipe" for ricin on the internet, used protective gloves and eyewear while he was mixing the chemicals in his room, and waited until his roommate was out of town to start working on the deadly poison. Miller said authorities think the student developed the idea to use ricin to kill after watching an episode of the TV crime drama "Breaking Bad".

Miller also said the resident adviser told authorities that the student had denied that he was going to use the toxin on himself in a suicide attempt. But when the adviser asked the student if he was going to use it on someone else, he (the student) "shrugged" his shoulders, Miller said. "This was deliberately thought out and well planned," Miller said. Miller also quoted from a Facebook message the student allegedly emailed to a friend during a dispute in which the student told the friend he was "useless" and that the only use for him would be if he were "chemically disincorporated" and his "parts were sold".

[byline: Keith L Alexander]

