[2] Wisconsin
Date: Tue 11 Nov 2014
Source: WBay.com [edited]
http://www.wbay.com/story/27346182/2014/11/10/oshkosh-ricin-suspect-to-be-tried-federally


The US Department of Justice says a male UW-Oshkosh student has been charged with possession of ricin in connection with an incident on 31 Oct 2014 that shut down 4 blocks of an Oshkosh neighborhood.

According to court documents, the male student extracted the toxin from castor plants and stored it in a residence he was living at in the 800 block of Frederick Street in Oshkosh. The material was taken to a lab in Virginia where it tested positive for ricin. The criminal complaint against him says the male student (the perpetrator) planned on testing the toxin on mice or insects.

[The student] was arrested on 31 Oct 2014 and held in the Winnebago County jail. He was transferred into federal custody [Mon 10 Nov 2014] and had his initial appearance in federal court. A preliminary hearing has been scheduled for [24 Nov 2014] and he will remain in custody until that time.

According to a search warrant filed in Winnebago County and the criminal complaint, the student made inquiries to 2 professors about making toxins from plants. The documents say he asked one professor how to make extractions from seeds. The professor told the student to ask a biology teacher to which the student alleged perpetrator responded "they are all interested in life, and I am interested in, like, ending it", according to the search warrant.

The warrant and criminal complaint say the [alleged perpetrator] then told another professor he spent time extracting "ribosomal-inhibiting proteins" from a source that he would not disclose to the professor.

[The 21 year old] was initially jailed for recklessly endangering safety and held in the Winnebago County Jail. Authorities ruled that there was sufficient probable cause in the case to hold him in custody for a reasonable amount of time without filing charges while they decided how to proceed with the case. The Winnebago County Jail says the male student was picked up by the FBI Monday morning [10 Nov 2014].

